Rolling window 24¶

From the rolling analysis we see that if the window is 24(daily) there is still deviation on the rolling mean that indicates that there is still seasonality is hidden in the data. When the window is 168(weekly), the rolling mean is stable and the 168 lag differenced detrend data has small devations; therefore it is good estimator of seasonality. When the rolling window is 720, the rolling mean is also stable however the 720 lag differenced detrend data shows more deviations from 0 than 168 lag differenced detrend data. Therefore choosing 168 for seasonality seems to be the best option.
In [55]:
data['z_data'] = (data['Tuketim_Miktari'] - data.Tuketim_Miktari.rolling(window=24).mean()) / data.Tuketim_Miktari.rolling(window=24).std()
data['zp_data'] = data['z_data'] - data['z_data'].shift(24)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3,figsize=(12, 9))
ax[0].plot(data.index, data.Tuketim_Miktari, label='raw data')
ax[0].plot(data.Tuketim_Miktari.rolling(window=24).mean(), label="rolling mean");
ax[0].plot(data.Tuketim_Miktari.rolling(window=24).std(), label="rolling std ");
ax[0].legend()

ax[1].plot(data.index, data.z_data, label="de-trended data")
ax[1].plot(data.z_data.rolling(window=24).mean(), label="rolling mean");
ax[1].plot(data.z_data.rolling(window=24).std(), label="rolling std ");
ax[1].legend()

ax[2].plot(data.index, data.zp_data, label="24 lag differenced de-trended data")
ax[2].plot(data.zp_data.rolling(window=24).mean(), label="rolling mean");
ax[2].plot(data.zp_data.rolling(window=24).std(), label="rolling std ");
ax[2].legend()


fig.suptitle('Rolling with window = 24', fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout()
fig.autofmt_xdate()

Plot ACF¶

When we look at the autocorrelations for weekly and monthly we see that weekly autocorrelations are almost 0.75 for the beginning of each day and the first differencing autocorrelations are always above 0.8. However, for monthly autocorrelations we see that both on original series' and first order differencing's autocorrelations drop below 0.8. This also indicates that weekly seasonality fits better.
In [417]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(211)
fig = plot_acf(timeseries, ax=ax1,
               title="Autocorrelation on Original Series",lags = 168) 
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(212)
fig = plot_acf(timeseries.diff().dropna(), ax=ax2, 
               title="1st Order Differencing",lags = 168)
fig.suptitle('ACFs with lag = 168', fontsize=16)

Decompositions¶

Hourly Decomposition¶

The hourly,daily, weekly and monthly decompositions are given below. The weekly decompositions' residuals follows better normal distribution than any other decomposition as expected since we have already mentioned that weekly seasonality is a good estimator. The monthly decompositions' residuals have more deviation than weekly and it follows a pattern for the whole data. However, weekly decomposition's residuals are more stable and doesn't follow a pattern for whole data. On the other hand, it deviates more at the last four week. That might be due to the consumption at the april doesn't follow the same seasonality as the first three months.
In [37]:
hourly_decom = seasonal_decompose(timeseries, model='additive',period =1)

Forecast¶

The ARMA with order(1,1) has the lowest AIC value so I will continue my analysis with it. To forecast the errors of the STL(seasonality-trend-level) model for the next day I will forecast the ARMA model. Then I will use the linear regression model to forecast trend value for the next day as calculated at the beginning of part 4. Finally I will add the seasonality values according to the corresponding weekday of the next day which is Wednesday (27.04.2016).
In [409]:
trend_forecast = [result_OLS.params.x1*i + result_OLS.params.const for i in (np.arange(2784,2808))]
total_forecast = results_1.forecast(24)[0] +  trend_forecast + weekly_decom.seasonal[24*2:24*3]
date = np.array('2016-04-27 00', dtype=np.datetime64)
new_index = date + np.arange(24)
total_forecast = pd.Series(total_forecast.values,index=new_index)
total_lower_ci = (results_1.forecast(24)[2])[:,1] + trend_forecast + weekly_decom.seasonal[24*2:24*3]
total_upper_ci = (results_1.forecast(24)[2])[:,0] + trend_forecast + weekly_decom.seasonal[24*2:24*3]
total_lower_ci = pd.Series(total_lower_ci.values,index=new_index)
total_upper_ci = pd.Series(total_upper_ci.values,index=new_index)
